    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Use asset objects to incorporate external files—such as image, sound, video, text, and binary data files—into your app’s records. You can also use assets in places where the data you want to assign to a field is more than a few kilobytes in size. To associate an asset with a record, assign it as the value of one of the record’s fields."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "CloudKit stores the content of an asset separately from the record that references it, but maintains close association with that record. When you save a record that has an asset, CloudKit saves both the record and the asset data to the server. Similarly, when you fetch the record, the server returns the record data and any assets. If multiple records refer to the same asset, however, CloudKit saves or fetches only one copy of the asset data. CloudKit saves only the asset data; it doesn’t save the filename or any other metadata for the file that you provide. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "When you download a record that contains an asset, CloudKit retains the asset data, but may delete it in the future to free up disk space. After fetching a record that contains an asset, you can retrieve the asset data with the URL in the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/cloudkit/ckasset/1515050-fileurl"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. If you want to ensure that the asset’s data remains local to the device, write the data to a file in your app’s local container directory and reference the data from the new file."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can’t delete asset data directly from the server. When you no longer want the data for an asset, remove all asset objects that point to that data from your records. For example, for a record that contains an asset as a field, set the value of the field to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/objectivec/nil-2gl"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". When no asset objects refer to the data, the server lazily deletes the asset data in the future, which could be up to several days later."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
